<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-499-669  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 499 669.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 7 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Intelsat sues Martin Marietta over botched satellite launch.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Martin Marietta Corp. (cases).andO;Ticker:    ML.andO;Topic:     International Telecommunications Satellite OrganizationSatellite CommunicationsSatellitesCourt CasesLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>INTELSAT SUES MARTIN MARIETTA OVER BOTCHED SATELLITE LAUNCH BALTIMORE,MARYLAND, U.S.A., 1990 SEP 7 (NB) -- The Intelsat communications satelliteconsortium is facing the most serious challenges to its hegemony ever.andO;Already under fire from Tongasat, a group sponsored by two Americanentrepreneurs and the government of Tonga which seeks to break up theconsortium's monopoly on satellite communications space, Intelsat now faces along court fight with one of the leading space launch companies, MartinMarietta.andM;Intelsat has filed a $400 million countersuit against Martin Marietta forallegedly botching the launch of a $157 million satellite last March.andP;  Theaction alleges negligence, breach of contract and misrepresentation.andP;  Itclaims that Martin Marietta miswired the satellite, failed to detect thefaulty wiring in preflight tests and lied that the computer and wiring werecompatible.andP;  It was called the Intelsat VI.andM;Intelsat's countersuit is in response to a lawsuit that Martin Marietta filedin July against the consortium, seeking a judgment declaring that MartinMarietta does not have to pay Intelsat for the problem.andP;  The satellite isstranded about 300 miles above the Earth, while it should be in ageosynchronous orbit at 22,000 miles up.andM;Intelsat claims losses of $400 million from the cost of the satellite, theamount paid to Martin Marietta before the launch and some $130 million inrevenues Intelstat expected to make from services supplied by the satellite.andM;A Martin Marietta spokesman told Newsbytes the company believes it willprevail.andP;  &quot;Their response to our lawsuit was expected and has no merit.andO;Under the contract, the relationship on risk or loss is clearly set forth,and says we're not liable for the satellite's failure to achieve orbit.andP;  Thecontract let Intelsat purchase insurance against mission failure, which theyfailed to do.&quot;andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900907/Press Contact: Elliott Miller, Martin Marietta,301-897-6000)</TEXT></DOC>